All the alloys, except M4 and MW1, showed homogeneous compression deformation, without any evidence of fracture. In the M4 and MW1 alloys, deformation localized inside macroscopic shear bands, which caused cracking and fracture along these bands at true compression strains of ~0.25 and 0.11,  respectively, after achieving peak true stress values of 1757 MPa and 1900 MPa (Fig.  4a ). Using a ¼ 1, b ¼ ffiffi ffi 3 p 2 a, a ¼ a mes from Table  3 , G ¼ G ROM and s 0.2 from Table  5 , the obstacle density b at the beginning of the plastic deformation was estimated for the studied alloys and the calculated values are shown in Table  5 . The calculated b are in the range from 1.53Â10 15 m -2 for alloy M1 to 4.95 x1015 m -2 for alloy MW1. These b values give the average distance between the obstacles of ~26 to 14 nm in the studied alloys. Such high number density of the obstacles in non-deformed singlephase alloys can only be related to solute atoms and their clusters. For example, the typical density of dislocation forest in annealed alloys is ~1x1011 to 3 x1012 m -2 , i.e. 3 to 4 orders of magnitude lower. The observed increase in b with increasing the concentration of the alloying elements in the same alloy families also supports the solidsolution strengthening mechanism in these alloys.
